---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Hammerstein.ai | Ray Weiss"
  description="Strategic-reasoning AI for tabletop wargames. Paste your board state, get back Auftragstaktik orders. $15 / month."
>
  <main class="px-6 py-24 lg:px-16">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <h1 class="font-sans text-4xl font-medium tracking-tight text-foreground lg:text-5xl">
        Hammerstein.ai
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-6 font-serif text-lg italic text-muted">
        Strategic-reasoning AI for tabletop wargames, built around the Hammerstein-Equord doctrine.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 font-serif text-lg text-foreground">
        Paste your board state, a status report, and the turn question. Get back Auftragstaktik orders.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-10 max-w-[72ch]">
        <div class="infra-meta">
          <span
            ><span class="dot live"></span><span class="k">Status</span><span class="v"
              >Live &middot; early access</span
            ></span
          >
          <span><span class="k">Price</span><span class="v">$15 / month</span></span>
          <span><span class="k">Limit</span><span class="v">120 turns / month</span></span>
          <span><span class="k">Demo</span><span class="v">5 turns / IP / day &middot; free</span></span>
        </div>
        <p class="mt-6 font-serif text-sm text-muted">
          Live: <a href="https://hammerstein.ai">hammerstein.ai</a>.
          Benchmark: <a href="https://hammerstein.ai/benchmark/">hammerstein.ai/benchmark</a>.
          Journal: <a href="https://hammerstein.ai/journal/">hammerstein.ai/journal</a>.
          The framework underneath: <a href="/hammerstein">the CLI</a> &middot; <a href="/hammerstein-model">the 7B model</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-body mt-12">
        <h2>What it does</h2>

        <p>
          Wargamer mode is the live surface. Paste your board state, a short
          status report, and the turn question you're trying to decide. The model
          returns kriegspiel-style Auftragstaktik orders &mdash; situation,
          intent, main effort, supporting effort, end-state &mdash; for the side
          you're playing. Same framework as <a href="/hammerstein">the
          open-source CLI</a>, applied to wargame turns instead of plan audits.
        </p>

        <h2>What's shipped</h2>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Text-input turns</strong> &mdash; board state + status +
            question &rarr; Auftragstaktik orders. Sonnet 4.6 wrapped in the
            Hammerstein system prompt. The primary surface.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Board-photo upload</strong> &mdash; JPG or PNG resized to
            1600px in your browser with EXIF rotation preserved, attached as a
            multimodal reference image per turn.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Rulebook ingest</strong> &mdash; paste rules text or drop a
            PDF; parsed client-side via pdf.js, never uploaded. Cited when a
            specific rule shapes the order.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Persistent campaign memory across machines</strong> &mdash;
            paid-tier campaigns sync server-side via Cloudflare D1. Start a
            campaign on your laptop, resume on your phone.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Anti-metagame ethical constraint</strong> &mdash; the model
            does not card-count or game hidden information; the constraint is a
            hard rule in the system prompt, not a courtesy. Challenge mode
            toggles it off when you want the AI playing without that restraint.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Benchmark</h2>

        <p>
          On the framework-discipline benchmark, the system prompt wins across
          model scales &mdash; frontier wraps (Opus 4.7 / Sonnet 4.6 / GPT-5),
          out-of-domain question sets, and a 7B distilled local model. v0.7
          human-judge results compiling. Methodology, per-generation results,
          and the replication kit live at
          <a href="https://hammerstein.ai/benchmark/">hammerstein.ai/benchmark</a>.
        </p>

        <h2>Pricing</h2>

        <p>
          $15 / month for 120 turns &mdash; sized for a real campaign cadence,
          not metered by the day. First 50 subscribers; pricing rises after.
          The free demo runs at 5 turns per IP per day for anyone who wants to
          test the surface before subscribing.
        </p>

        <h2>Try it</h2>

        <p>
          Live at <a href="https://hammerstein.ai">hammerstein.ai</a>. The free
          demo doesn't require a subscription &mdash; just paste a turn and see
          what comes back. The subscriber tier unlocks the 120-turn-per-month
          cap and cross-machine persistent campaign memory.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
